User: Hi Assistant!

Assistant: Hey User! What can I help you with?

User: Can you please give me an example of how to use context API?

Assistant: Sure thing! Let's say we want to display different content depending on whether someone has logged into our app or not. We could do this using conditional rendering:

```javascript 
import React from'react';
import { useContext } from'react';

const App = () => {
    const userContext = useContext(UserContext);

    return (
        <div>
            {!userContext.isLoggedIn && <p>Please log in</p>}
            {userContext.isLoggedIn &&
                <>
                    Welcome back!
                    {/* Display other components here */}
                </>
            }
        </div>
    );
};

export default App;
```
In this code snippet, we first import `useContext` hook from react library. Then inside component function body,we create new variable called "userContext" which will hold value returned by calling useContext() method passing reference to custom created context object as argument. Next line checks condition based upon boolean property present within same object i.e., isLoggedIn. If its false then only one paragraph element gets rendered otherwise both paragraphs alongwith additional JSX elements get displayed accordingly.

This approach allows us to easily manage state across multiple components without having to pass props down through each level manually. Additionally, since contexts provide access to shared data via their values rather than directly modifying them (like local states), they make it easier to maintain consistency between related pieces of information throughout application lifecycle.
